of the nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, the book concentrates on the development of Marxist-inspired writing from the 1920s to the end of the twentieth century. Besides devoting attention to both social and theoretical backgrounds, this study provides critical commentary on work by prominent writers who spent part of their literary careers as Communist Party members, including Dorothy Livesay, Patrick Anderson, Milton Acorn, and George Ryga, as well as less well known but more fervent Communists such as Margaret Fairley, Dyson Carter, Joe Wallace, Stanley Ryerson, and Jean-Jules Richard. Although primarily concerned with the older generation of Marxists who flourished between the 1920s and the 1970s, the book also includes a chapter on the post-1970s “New Left.”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian literaturexHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aCanadian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aCommunism and literaturexHistoryx20th centuryxCanada. 0aCommunism and literaturezCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitics and literaturexHistoryx20th centuryxCanada. 0aPolitics and literaturezCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aProgressivism in literature. 0aRadicalism in literature. 0aRadicalismxHistoryx20th centuryxCanada. 0aRadicalismzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 4aLiterary Criticism. 4aLiterary Criticism: Canadian Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920829240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889208292423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889208292/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Comp